# API Design Guidelines

Directives for designing and reviewing APIs. For detailed security patterns, defer to `security.mdc` and `engineering-security.mdc`.

---

## REST Principles

### Resource-based URLs

- Use nouns, not verbs: `/api/users`, `/api/orders` — not `/api/getUsers` or `/api/createOrder`
- Use plural nouns for collections: `/api/users` — not `/api/user`
- Nest resources only when there is a true parent-child relationship: `/api/users/123/posts`
- Avoid query params for resource identity: prefer `/api/users/123` over `/api/user?id=123`

### HTTP Methods and Status Codes

| Method | Use for | Success |
|--------|---------|---------|
| GET | Read (idempotent) | 200 OK |
| POST | Create | 201 Created |
| PUT | Full replace | 200 OK |
| PATCH | Partial update | 200 OK |
| DELETE | Remove | 204 No Content |

| Status | Use when |
|--------|----------|
| 200 | Success with body |
| 201 | Created; include `Location` header |
| 204 | Success, no body |
| 400 | Validation error, bad request |
| 401 | Unauthenticated |
| 403 | Unauthorised (authenticated but forbidden) |
| 404 | Resource not found |
| 409 | Conflict (e.g. duplicate) |
| 429 | Rate limit exceeded |
| 500 | Internal server error |

---

## Request/Response Models

- Define explicit DTOs for request bodies; do not accept raw `any` or untyped objects
- Use separate DTOs for create vs update (create: required fields; update: optional fields)
- Wrap success responses in a consistent envelope; use a standard error envelope
- Exclude internal fields (e.g. `passwordHash`) from response DTOs
- Use ISO 8601 for dates in JSON

**Success envelope:** `{ data: T, message?: string, timestamp: string }`

**Error envelope:** `{ error: { code: string, message: string, details?: object }, timestamp: string }`

---

## Versioning Strategies

| Strategy | When to use | Example |
|----------|-------------|---------|
| URL | Public APIs, breaking changes | `/api/v1/users`, `/api/v2/users` |
| Header | Content negotiation, same URL | `Accept: application/vnd.company.api-v1+json` |
| Query | Internal APIs, optional version | `/api/users?version=1` |

- Prefer URL versioning for public APIs; it is explicit and cache-friendly
- Do not version by default; version only when the resource contract changes meaningfully
- Support at least one previous version during deprecation; document sunset dates

---

## Pagination and Filtering

### Pagination

- Support `page` and `limit` (or `per_page`) for offset-based pagination; cap `limit` (e.g. max 100)
- For large or real-time datasets, prefer cursor-based pagination: `?cursor=xyz&limit=20`
- Include pagination metadata in responses: `page`, `limit`, `total`, `totalPages`, `hasNext`, `hasPrev` (or equivalent)
- Default sort: `createdAt` descending unless the use case requires otherwise

### Filtering

- Use query params for filters: `?status=active&role=admin`
- Support date ranges: `?createdFrom=2024-01-01&createdTo=2024-12-31`
- Support search: `?search=term`; document behaviour (exact match, partial, etc.)
- Whitelist filterable fields; reject unknown params or document them

### Response shape

- Offset-based: `{ data: T[], pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages, hasNext, hasPrev } }`
- Cursor-based: `{ data: T[], nextCursor?: string, hasMore: boolean }`

---

## Error Handling

- Use a base `ApiException` with `statusCode`, `code`, `message`, and optional `details`
- Derive specific exceptions: `ValidationException` (400), `NotFoundException` (404), `UnauthorisedException` (401)
- Apply a global exception filter so all errors return the same envelope shape
- Do not expose stack traces, DB errors, or internal paths to clients
- Log full error context server-side; return minimal, safe messages to clients
- Use machine-readable `code` values (e.g. `VALIDATION_ERROR`, `NOT_FOUND`) for client handling

---

## API Documentation

- Generate OpenAPI/Swagger from code or maintain a spec file; keep it in sync with implementation
- Document every endpoint: summary, description, request/response schemas, status codes
- Document query params, path params, and request body schemas
- Include example requests and responses for non-trivial endpoints
- Document authentication requirements (e.g. Bearer token, API key)
- For GraphQL: publish schema; document custom scalars, directives, and deprecations

---

## GraphQL Directives

### Schema design

- Use `input` types for mutation arguments; avoid deep nesting
- Use `!` for non-null where appropriate; avoid over-constraining
- Prefer specific field names over generic ones
- Deprecate fields with `@deprecated(reason: "...")`; do not remove without a migration path

### Resolver patterns

- Keep resolvers thin; delegate business logic to services
- Use DataLoader (or equivalent) for batched lookups to prevent N+1 queries
- Validate and sanitise inputs in resolvers; do not trust client data
- Return `null` for missing optional data; use errors for exceptional cases

### N+1 prevention

- Batch database queries by parent ID in list resolvers
- Use DataLoader or similar batching/caching for foreign-key lookups
- Avoid per-item queries in list resolvers; prefer bulk fetches

---

## API Security

- Require authentication by default; opt-in for public endpoints
- Validate JWT (or equivalent) on protected routes; reject invalid or expired tokens
- Enforce RBAC or resource-level checks; verify the caller can access the requested resource
- Apply rate limiting per client/IP; use stricter limits for auth and write endpoints
- Use HTTPS only; set security headers (HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options, etc.)
- For detailed patterns, see `security.mdc` and `engineering-security.mdc`

---

## Caching Directives

- Cache GET responses where data is stable and idempotent; avoid caching user-specific or volatile data without care
- Use `Cache-Control` headers: `max-age`, `private`/`public`, `no-store` where appropriate
- Support `If-None-Match` (ETag) or `If-Modified-Since` for conditional requests; return 304 when unchanged
- Use Redis (or similar) for shared cache when running multiple instances; define TTLs per resource type
- Invalidate or version cache keys when data changes; avoid stale reads for critical data
- Do not cache responses that include sensitive or user-specific data without proper scoping

---

## API Testing Directives

- Write integration tests that hit real HTTP endpoints (or equivalent); mock external services only
- Test success paths and expected error paths (400, 401, 403, 404)
- Test validation: required fields, formats, ranges; assert error codes and messages
- Use a test client (e.g. `supertest`, `WebApplicationFactory`) rather than unit-testing controllers in isolation
- Mock or stub databases/external APIs to keep tests fast and deterministic
- Assert response shape, status codes, and critical fields; avoid overspecifying implementation details

---

## Checklist

- [ ] Resource-based URLs; correct HTTP methods and status codes
- [ ] Request/response DTOs defined; no internal fields in responses
- [ ] Versioning strategy chosen and applied consistently
- [ ] Pagination and filtering supported; limits enforced
- [ ] Standardised error envelope; global exception handling
- [ ] OpenAPI/Swagger (or equivalent) documented and up to date
- [ ] GraphQL: schema published; N+1 avoided via batching
- [ ] Authentication and authorisation enforced; rate limiting applied
- [ ] Caching strategy defined for cacheable endpoints
- [ ] Integration tests cover main flows and error cases
